Bank of China, China Merchants Bank: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-04-28T10:18:39Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-28/bank-of-china-china-merchants-bank-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  fell 0.4 percent to 23,805.63. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, slid 1 percent to 13,319.96.  Bank of China Ltd. (3988)  (3988 HK): The nation’s third-largest
lender by market value said first-quarter net income rose 28
percent to 33.4 billion yuan ($5.14 billion) from a year
earlier. That compares with the median 31.7 billion yuan
estimate of eight analysts in a Bloomberg News survey. The stock
fell 0.7 percent to HK$4.34.  China Merchants Bank Co. (3968 HK): The nation’s sixth-
largest lender said first-quarter profit rose 49 percent to 8.8
billion yuan from a year earlier. The stock climbed 0.6 percent
to HK$20.40.  China Oilfield Services Ltd. (2883)  (2883 HK): The unit of the
nation’s largest offshore oil producer posted a 1.2
percent drop in first-quarter profit compared with a year
earlier as rig utilization rates declined. Net income fell to
965.9 million yuan from 977.3 million yuan a year earlier, the
unit of state-owned China National Offshore Oil Corp. said in a
statement to the Hong Kong stock exchange today. The stock
declined 1.7 percent to HK$15.90.  Huadian Power International Co. (1071)  (1071 HK): China’s fourth-
biggest electricity producer said it swung to a first-quarter
net loss of 264.6 million yuan from net income of 77.2 million
yuan the same period a year earlier. The stock increased 1.3
percent to HK$1.61.  Hui Xian Real Estate Investment Trust (87001 HK):  Hong
Kong ’s first stock sale denominated in yuan will begin trading
today after selling units at the low end of a price range. The
trust controlled by Hong Kong billionaire  Li Ka-shing  raised
10.5 billion yuan selling units at 5.24 yuan each, according to
a statement to the Hong Kong stock exchange yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Tokyo at 
